  x=4, y=5: crossings at n=[1], values=[1]

======================================================================
  PART 5: THE DOUBLING FORMULA AND 5·11=55
======================================================================

Fibonacci doubling formula: F(2n) = F(n)·L(n)

At n=5:
  F(10) = F(5)·L(5) = 5·11 = 55

Since L(5) = J(5) = 11, we also have:
  F(10) = F(5)·J(5) = 5·11 = 55

This connects Fibonacci doubling to Jacobsthal!

Iterating the doubling formula from n=5:
  F(5) = 5
  F(10) = F(5)·L(5) = 5·11 = 55
  F(20) = F(10)·L(10) = 55·123 = 6765

======================================================================
  PART 6: TOURNAMENT SIGNIFICANCE
======================================================================

In tournament theory, the key evaluations are:
  H(T) = I(CG(T), 2)  — Hamiltonian path count
  I₃ = I(CG(T), 3)    — the 'secondary evaluation'

The ratio I₃/H approaches 3/2 as cycles grow.
More precisely: I₃ = (9H - 5 - 6α₁) / 4

The number 5 appears in this formula!
I₃ = (9H - 5 - 6α₁) / 4
  The '5' here is F(5) = L(5)/11 · 5 = the bridge number.

At the 'typical' tournament where α₁ ≈ H/2:
  I₃ ≈ (9H - 5 - 3H) / 4 = (6H - 5) / 4
  I₃/H ≈ 6/4 - 5/(4H) = 3/2 - 5/(4H)

The approach to 3/2 is controlled by 5/(4H).
So 5 governs the RATE at which I₃/H → 3/2.

And 3/2 = the product of convergence rates:
  (1/2 rate for k-nacci) · 3 = 3/2
  or: ratio of key limits = 3/2 = (1+x)/x at x=2

THE COMPLETE PICTURE:
  F(5) = 5 (Fibonacci fixed point)
  L(5) = 11 (Lucas generates decimal pair)
  J(5) = 11 (Jacobsthal agrees at this point)
  I₃ = (9H - 5 - 6α₁)/4 (5 appears in OCF formula)
  I₃/H → 3/2 - 5/(4H) (5 controls approach rate)

All of these are DIFFERENT MANIFESTATIONS of 5 = 2+3
in the recurrence landscape.

======================================================================
  PART 7: JACOBSTHAL LEVELS AND 5
======================================================================

The integer-root levels of f(n) = f(n-1) + x·f(n-2):

  k x=k(k-1)           Roots     J_x(5)     L_x(5)
  1        0             1,0          1          1
  2        2            2,-1         11         31
  3        6            3,-2         55        211
  4       12            4,-3        181        781
  5       20            5,-4        461       2101
  6       30            6,-5        991       4651
  7       42            7,-6       1891       9031
  8       56            8,-7       3305      15961
  9       72            9,-8       5401      26281

PATTERN: J_x(5) at the integer-root levels
  k=1: J₀(5) = 1·(1⁵-0⁵)/1 = 1
  k=2: J₂(5) = (32+1)/3 = 11
  k=3: J₆(5) = (243-(-2)⁵)/5 = (243+32)/5 = 275/5 = 55
  k=4: J₁₂(5) = (1024-(-3)⁵)/7 = (1024+243)/7 = 1267/7 = 181

J₆(5) = 55 = F(10) = F(5)·L(5) = 5·11!

So the level-3 Jacobsthal at n=5 equals the DOUBLED Fibonacci!
J₆(5) = F(2·5) = F(5)·L(5)

This is NOT a coincidence. It follows from:
  J_6(n) = (3^n - (-2)^n) / 5
  F(2n) = F(n)·L(n)
  At n=5: J_6(5) = (3^5 + 2^5)/5 = (243+32)/5 = 55 = 5·11

Checking J₆(n) vs F(2n):
  n=1: J₆(n)=       1, F(2n)=       1 ✓
  n=2: J₆(n)=       1, F(2n)=       3 
  n=3: J₆(n)=       7, F(2n)=       8 
  n=4: J₆(n)=      13, F(2n)=      21 
  n=5: J₆(n)=      55, F(2n)=      55 ✓
  n=6: J₆(n)=     133, F(2n)=     144 
  n=7: J₆(n)=     463, F(2n)=     377 
  n=8: J₆(n)=    1261, F(2n)=     987 
  n=9: J₆(n)=    4039, F(2n)=    2584 

Only matches at n=1 and n=5!
n=1: J₆(1)=1=F(2) trivial
n=5: J₆(5)=55=F(10) the KEY match

Done.
